@node Live Presentation üé¨
@section Live Presentation üé¨

@enumerate
@item
Select a region of text you wish to display
@item
Call @code{moc-focus}.  (this is a command worth binding)
@end enumerate

Now you are within the focus buffer.  It uses a modal interface@comma{} like magit@comma{} to quickly author changes and reference the controls.  To see the transient modal interface@comma{} call @code{moc-focus-dispatch} or press the @samp{h} binding.

By default the cursor is hidden.  This is because usually you want to make screenshots or do playback.  To activate an ephemeral cursor@comma{} press @samp{.} for @code{moc-subtle-cursor-mode}.  (this mode may be useful for presentation in general).  The subtle cursor disappears whenever you aren't using it!  Very beneficial.

You can also modify the results several ways:
@itemize
@item
Select a region and highlight it with @samp{l}
@item
Remap the faces with @samp{r}
@item
Clear highlights with @samp{c}
@end itemize

üí° Maneuvering the point with packages like @code{avy} does not require a cursor.  Highlighting by simply using the region is also viable for live demonstration.

üí° While the buffer defaults to read-only to be less touchy@comma{} you can of course turn this off with @code{read-only-mode} to make quick touch-ups to the text.  Keep in mind@comma{} the backing data structures may become off depending on the latest implementation üë∑

@node Persisted Playback ‚ñ∂Ô∏è
@section Persisted Playback ‚ñ∂Ô∏è

When you have arrived at a starting or intermediate point you want to play back exactly within Emacs@comma{} the @samp{w} key calls @code{moc-focus-kill-ring-save}.  An expression will be saved to your kill ring that re-creates the currently visible state.

Copy this expression wherever appropriate@comma{} such as the body of a babel block configured as a step in @ref{Top,dslide,,dslide,}.

üöß Playback is not yet 100% the same as doing a fresh capture with @code{moc-focus}.

@node Saving Screenshots üì∏
@section Saving Screenshots üì∏

It is of great convenience if the files are saved in the correct place.  Configure @code{moc-screenshot-dir} to be a function that calculates the correct location based on your current project directory.

Here's an example that calculates where to save screenshots based on the project directory.

@code{moc-focus-base-buffer} is bound to a source buffer when the current buffer is an @samp{MoC Focus} buffer.  You can use this value to decided based on the source buffer.
@lisp
;; Add this to your use-package :config section
 (defun my-screenshots-dir ()
  (interactive)
  ;; When taking screenshots from a focus buffer@comma{} it sets
  ;; `moc-focus-base-buffer' so that you can decide based on the base
  ;; buffer@comma{} not the focus buffer@comma{} which has no associated file.
  (with-current-buffer (or moc-focus-base-buffer
                           (current-buffer))
    (expand-file-name
     "screenshots/"
     (or (when-let ((p (project-current))) (project-root p))
         (temporary-file-directory)))))

;; configure the function to be called to calculate the correct options at
;; runtime
(setopt moc-screenshot-dir #'my-screenshots-dir)

@end lisp
Now just configure the save type@comma{} @code{moc-screenshot-type}@comma{} which uses the same types as supported by @code{x-export-frames}.

@node Presenting üéõÔ∏è
@chapter Presenting üéõÔ∏è

It is recommended to bind the @code{moc-dispatch} interface to a key.  This interface shows many relevant configuration states and provides options to change them.  It also includes some built-in Emacs behaviors@comma{} consolidating these controls into a transient interface.

@itemize
@item
@code{moc-quiet-mode} suppresses some but not all messages.  User commands that generate @code{user-error} and some other messages may still get through.  ‚ö†Ô∏è Leaving this on can result in confusion@comma{} but it is on by default when using @code{moc-focus} because such messages almost always interrupt taking screenshots.
@item
@code{moc-face-remap} can apply multiple face remappings according to preset profiles.
@item
@code{moc-subtle-cursor-mode} is similar to @code{blink-cursor-mode} but hides itself after motion.  You can use it like a laser pointer during presentation and it gets back out of the way on its own.
@item
@code{moc-fixed-frame} creates hooks on a target frame that preserve its dimensions.  It has preset resolutions@comma{} so if you always present or capture the screen at target dimensions@comma{} it's great.

üöß There is an issue with the size maintenance when a transient prefix is active.  Resizing the default text scale can exhibit the issue.  Dismissing the transient fixes it for now.
@end itemize

